C++17 headless 3D simulation engine. 

It has:

    basic 3D math (Vec3)
    entity system
    simple physics (velocity-based movement)
    fixed timestep loop
    observer-style publisher (console output)
    clean separation: Simulation → FrameData → Publisher

You can later swap the publisher with socket / JSON / UI.

What this POC demonstrates
    Engine loop (fixed timestep)
    Data-oriented frame output
    Decoupled interface (Observer pattern style)
    Extensible structure (fits your design-pattern approach)

-----------------------------------
What to improve next (this is where it becomes powerful)

If you push this a bit, it becomes a serious system:

1. Replace ConsolePublisher
    JSON exporter
    TCP streaming
    shared memory

2. Add Components (ECS direction)

Instead of Entity struct:

    Transform
    Physics
    Render (future UI)

3. Command System

Control simulation:

    pause
    spawn entity
    change velocity

4. Time system
    fixed timestep vs variable timestep
    pause/resume

5. Plug into real UI

    You could feed this into:

    a Python dashboard
    a web frontend
    or even Unreal Engine as a data source

One honest suggestion
    Right now this is a good POC, but the real value comes if you:
    turn this into a plugin-based simulation framework (like your other projects)
    That would genuinely stand out in interviews and real systems work.
-------------------------------------------
If you run that program, 
the console output is just textual frame-by-frame state of your simulation—no graphics, just structured data.
Here’s exactly what it looks like (approximate, values change every frame):

Frame 0
  Entity 1 -> Pos(0.016, 0.0032, 0.008)
  Entity 2 -> Pos(4.992, 1.0016, -1.9952)
  Entity 3 -> Pos(-2.9968, 1.9984, 1.0064)

Frame 1
  Entity 1 -> Pos(0.032, 0.0065, 0.016)
  Entity 2 -> Pos(4.984, 1.0032, -1.9904)
  Entity 3 -> Pos(-2.9936, 1.9968, 1.0128)

Frame 2
  Entity 1 -> Pos(0.048, 0.0099, 0.024)
  Entity 2 -> Pos(4.976, 1.0048, -1.9856)
  Entity 3 -> Pos(-2.9904, 1.9952, 1.0192)

  What you’re seeing

    Each block = one simulation frame
        Frame 0, 1, 2... → time progression
        Each Entity → object in your 3D world
        Pos(x, y, z) → actual 3D coordinates

    So instead of rendering:
        a cube on screen
        you’re printing its position in space 

    Why this matters (don’t overlook this)

    This output is basically:
        a real-time data stream of your simulation

    That means:
        another program can read it
        a UI can visualize it
        you can log it, replay it, analyze it
--------------------------------------------------
One important insight
    You are not “printing data”.
    You are:
        publishing simulation state
    Console is just:
        a debugging subscriber